stylometry: Our group project consisted of a break-even analysis for Professional Development. The department is currently facing low enrollments, so we wanted to see how much costs the company incurs, and how many participants will have to take a course in order for the company to break even. We collected all of the costs (costs of printing/mailing the catalogs, costs of the online system, and costs of the instructors). From this, we made a break-even analysis model. We determined the response rate based on number of catalogs mailed. This model showed us how many participants needed to register for a course in order for the company to break-even. Then we figured that most companies do not just want to break-even, but to turn a profit as well. So we took the expenses incurred from the last problem, doubled those, and determined how many participants needed to take a course in order to reach our expenses doubled. We learned that the outcome of this model would be beneficial for Professional Development when determining if they should limit the number of catalogs they send out and also allows them to see if they should offer any special promotions etc. in order to reach their break-even point (or doubled expenses point). In order for Professional Development to break-even this summer, there would need to be a response rate of 3% (200 some participants, I do not remember the exact number), which from previous semesters, this is possible. In order to double expenses, Professional Development would need a response rate of 11% (500 some participants I believe), which the department has been pretty close to doing in the past. When using this model in the future, the company would just have to adjust instructor pay rate based on the number of instructors that semester and adjust the number of catalogs mailed (if that number chamged).
